Jim Margolis (born April 30, 1955) is a political consultant and communications executive based in Washington, D.C. He served as a Senior Advisor to Barack Obama in both his 2008<ref>{{cite web|last=Cillizza|first=Chris|title=Margolis Joins Obama's Campaign|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/eye-on-2008/obama-adds-margolis.html|publisher=The Washington Post|work=27 April 2007}}</ref> and 2012<ref name=21 November 2011>{{cite web|last=Rutenberg|first=Jim|title=Team Obama Gears Up for 2012|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/27/sunday-review/Team-Obama-Gears-Up-for-2012.html?pagewanted=all&_r=1&|work=21 November 2011|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> campaigns for the White House, taking a lead role in each cycle<U+2019>s half-billion dollar<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Reid|title=2012 Campaign-Ad Spending Poised to Smash 2008 Record|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/2012-presidential-campaign/2012-campaign-ad-spending-poised-to-smash-2008-record-20120629|publisher=National Journal|work=29 June 2013}}</ref> advertising effort and helping direct the campaign as a member of the core strategic team.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dickinson|first=Tim|title=The Obama Campaign's Real Heroes|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/the-obama-campaigns-real-heroes-20121126|publisher=Rolling Stone|work=7 December 2012}}</ref> He also served as co-producer of Mr. Obama<U+2019>s two presidential inaugurals<ref>{{cite web|last=Stolberg|first=Sheryl Gay|title=Adjusting Expectations for Obama's 2nd Inaugural|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/24/us/politics/obamas-2nd-inaugural-will-likely-draw-fewer-to-capital.html?pagewanted=all|publisher=The New York Times|work=23 November 2012}}</ref> and Mr. Obama<U+2019>s two national nominating conventions (Denver, 2008; Charlotte, 2012).<ref>{{cite web|last=Rutenberg|first=Jim|title=Democrats Say U.S. Is Better Off Than Four Years Ago|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/04/us/politics/democrats-say-us-is-better-off-than-4-years-ago.html?pagewanted=all|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref> Margolis is a senior partner at GMMB, Inc.,<ref>{{cite web|title=GMMB|url=http://www.gmmb.com/}}</ref> a strategic communications firm and advertising agency known for its work with political leaders, nonprofits and corporations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cillizza|first=Chris|title=Margolis Joins Obama's Campaign|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/eye-on-2008/obama-adds-margolis.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=27 April 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dobbins|first=Elizabeth|title=OTC with Jim Margolis, OC <U+2019>78, and Senior Advisor to President Obama|url=http://oberlinreview.org/article/otc-jim-margolis-oc-78-and-senior-advisor-presiden/|newspaper=Oberlin Review|date=15 February 2013}}</ref> Previously he served as chief of staff to US Senator Kent Conrad (D-ND),<ref>{{cite news|title=Congressional Record, U.S. Senate, Kent Conrad, D-North Dakota, Farewell to the Senate|url=http://www.c-spanvideo.org/videoLibrary/transcript/transcript.php?id=211996|newspaper=CSPAN|date=12 December 12}}</ref> chief of staff to US Congressman Howard Wolpe (D-MI),<ref>{{cite news|last=Estepa|first=Jessica|title=Former Michigan Rep. Howard Wolpe Dies at Age 71|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/Former-Michigan-Rep-Howard-Wolpe-Dies-at-age-71-209850-1.html|newspaper=Roll Call|date=27 October 2011}}</ref> and Deputy Director of Communications for Vice President Walter Mondale<U+2019>s presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Teinowitz|first=Ira|title=The Player: Kerry camp taps Margolis to devise media strategy|url=http://adage.com/article/news/player-kerry-camp-taps-margolis-devise-media-strategy/49086/|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=12 May 2003}}</ref>

== Early Life ==
Margolis is the fifth child of Frederick Margolis,<ref>{{cite news|title=Margolis was a doctor who made a difference|newspaper=Kalamazoo Gazette|date=12 February 1991}}</ref> a pediatrician,<ref>{{cite news|title=OBITUARY: MARGOLIS, Dr. Fredrick J, Pediatrician, Community Activist, Educator, Researcher, Inventor|newspaper=Kalamazoo Gazette|date=10 February 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mah|first=Linda|title=Dr. Margolis, a gentle giant among children, dies at 75|newspaper=Kalamazoo Gazette|date=2/10/91}}</ref> film producer,<ref>{{cite web|title='Ounce of Prevention' Is Doctor's Theme|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_9shAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mqAFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2397%2C3909279|publisher=Reading Eagle|accessdate=26 August 1976}}</ref> and inventor,<ref>{{cite news|title=Margolis|newspaper=Encore Magazine|date=1990 September}}</ref> and Elizabeth Rieger,<ref>{{cite news|last=Spencer|first=Steven|title=They're Saving Lives in Navajo-Land|newspaper=The Saturday Evening Post|date=23 April 1955}}</ref> a social worker. He was born in Albuquerque, NM when his father served in the US Public Health Service directing health care on a Navajo Indian reservation (Ft. Defiance, AZ).<ref>{{cite news|title=MARGOLIS, Elizabeth Hays Rieger Age 95 of Kalamazoo|url=http://obits.mlive.com/obituaries/kalamazoo/obituary-print.aspx?n=elizabeth-margolis&pid=155107718|newspaper=Kalamazoo Gazette|date=18 December 2011}}</ref> Margolis grew up in Kalamazoo, Michigan, attended Kalamazoo public schools and graduated from Kalamazoo Central High School (1973).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jim Margolis, Class of 1973|url=https://www.alumniclass.com/kalamazoocentral/profile?u=3416422|publisher=Kalamazoo Central High School Alumni|accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> During his middle school years he became active in politics and elections.<ref>{{cite news|last=Axelrod|first=David|title=Organizers reflect their candidates|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=5 February 1984}}</ref> He headed a regional student group, Students for Better Education at age 14, was hired as field director for a congressional campaign at age 15 and served as the student representative to the Board of Education at age 17. Margolis received his BA from Oberlin College in 1978 with a double major in Government and Communications Studies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dobbins|first=Elizabeth|title=OTC with Jim Margolis, OC '78, and Senior Advisor to President Obama|url=http://oberlinreview.org/article/otc-jim-margolis-oc-78-and-senior-advisor-presiden/|publisher=Obelin Review|date=15 February 2013}}</ref>

== Political Career ==
Immediately after graduating from college, Margolis was hired to manage the long-shot congressional campaign of Howard Wolpe,<ref>{{cite web|title=Howard Wolpe Wikipedia Page|url=[[Howard Wolpe}}]]</ref> a state representative (MI-46th district) and former professor at Western Michigan University.<ref>{{cite news|last=Axelrod|first=David|title=Organizers reflect their candidates|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=5 February 1984}}</ref> The long-shot Wolpe defeated Republican incumbent Garry Brown in November 1978<ref>{{cite news|title=Archive: Howard Wolpe profile from 1992 Kalamazoo Gazette (with photo gallery)|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2011/10/archive_howard_wolpe_profile_f.html|newspaper=Kalamazoo Gazette|date=13 December 1991, 26 October 2011}}</ref> and Margolis, at age 22, came to Washington as Wolpe<U+2019>s chief of staff.<ref>{{cite news|last=Estepa|first=Jessica|title=Former Michigan Rep. Howard Wolpe Dies at Age 71|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/Former-Michigan-Rep-Howard-Wolpe-Dies-at-age-71-209850-1.html|newspaper=Roll Call|date=27 October 2011}}</ref> At the time, he was the youngest executive assistant on Capitol Hill.<ref>{{cite news|last=Axelrod|first=David|title=Organizers reflect on their candidates|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=5 February 1984}}</ref>

At 26, Margolis became <U+201C>Walter Mondale<U+2019>s man in Illinois,"<ref>{{cite news|last=Axelrod|first=David|title=Organizers reflect on their candidates|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=5 February 1984}}</ref> the state director for Mondale<U+2019>s key presidential primary win in the state. Next he served as state director for Mondale<U+2019>s North Carolina win,<ref>{{cite news|last=Gailey|first=Phil|title=BRIEFING; The Mondale Team Today|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1985/02/09/us/briefing-the-mondale-team-today.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 February 1985|author2=Warren Weaver Jr.}}</ref> and then in the general election, became Deputy Director of Communications at the national headquarters in Washington.<ref>{{cite news|last=Teinowitz|first=Ira|title=The Player: Kerry camp taps Margolis to devise media strategy|url=http://adage.com/article/news/player-kerry-camp-taps-margolis-devise-media-strategy/49086/|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=12 May 2003}}</ref>

Margolis joined GMMB (then Greer & Associates) in February 1985.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gailey|first=Phil|title=BRIEFING; The Mondale Team Today|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1985/02/09/us/briefing-the-mondale-team-today.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 February 1985|author2=Warren Weaver Jr.}}</ref> In 1986 he led the strategy and advertising efforts for two upset U.S. Senate wins, Brock Adams (D-WA) who defeated Republican Senator Slade Gorton, and Kent Conrad (D-ND) who defeated Republican Senator Mark Andrews.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Consultants Scorecard|journal=Campaigns and Elections|year=1986|month=November/December|pages=33-40}}</ref> Campaign and Elections magazine named Margolis a Rising Star.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Rising Stars|journal=Campaigns and Elections|year=1988|month=July|volume=9|series=2}}</ref> In January 1987, Margolis took a leave of absence from his firm and became Senator Conrad<U+2019>s first chief of staff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Congressional Record, U.S. Senate. Kent Conrad, D-North Dakota, Farewell to the Senate|url=http://www.c-spanvideo.org/videoLibrary/transcript/transcript.php?id=211996|publisher=CSPAN|accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=James|first=Kathleen|title=Hill Climbers|newspaper=Roll Call|date=13 September 1987|page=19}}</ref> In January 1988 he returned to GMMB.<ref>{{cite news|title=Conrad's staff chief is retiring|newspaper=Grand Forks Herald|date=5 August 1987}}</ref>

Nationally, Margolis is considered one of the top Democratic political consultants in the nation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Anderson|first=Heather|title=Obama<U+2019>s senior adviser to discuss political advertising at Dole Institute event|url=http://archive.news.ku.edu/2011/april/8/margolis.shtml|newspaper=KU News Release|date=8 April 2011}}</ref> winning key national and statewide races. Over the years Margolis<U+2019> senate clients have included: Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid (D-NV), Senator Max Baucus (D-MT), Senator Jeff Bingaman (D-NM), Senator Barbara Boxer (D-CA), Senator Brock Adams (D-WA),<ref>{{cite journal|title=Consultants Scorecard|journal=Campaigns and Elections|year=1986|month=November/December|volume=7|pages=33-40}}</ref> Senator Byron Dorgan (D-ND), Senator Ron Wyden (D-ND), Senator Bob Menendez(D-NJ), Senator John Kerry (D-MA),<ref>{{cite web|title=2002 SENATE RACES|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/htdocs/pdf/c2002_03.pdf|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=2002-2003}}</ref> Senator Kent Conrad (D-ND) and Senator Mark Warner (D-VA).<ref>{{cite news|last=Anderson|first=Heather|title=Obama<U+2019>s senior adviser to discuss political advertising at Dole Institute event|url=http://archive.news.ku.edu/2011/april/8/margolis.shtml|newspaper=KU News|date=8 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|title=Aggressive Ads for Obama, at the Ready|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/09/us/politics/obamas-media-team-has-aggressive-ads-at-the-ready.html?pagewanted=all&_r=2&|newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lizza|first=Ryan|title=Pop Warner|url=http://www.newrepublic.com/article/politics/mark-warner-virginia-democrat|newspaper=The New Republic|date=29 October 2006}}</ref> In addition Margolis has worked on behalf of many governors,<ref>{{cite news|last=Anderson|first=Heather|title=Obama<U+2019>s senior adviser to discuss political advertising at Dole Institute event|url=http://archive.news.ku.edu/2011/april/8/margolis.shtml|newspaper=KU News|date=8 April 2011}}</ref> members of Congress, statewide initiatives,<ref>{{cite news|last=Trygstad|first=Kyle|title=Shop Talk: The Winning and Losing Consultants of the '12 Cycle|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/shop_talk_the_winning_and_losing_consultants_of_the_12_cycle-219079-1.html?zkPrintable=true|newspaper=Roll Call|date=13 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Aaron C.|title=Politically connected firms hit jackpot in Maryland casino fight|url=http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2012-11-17/local/35503824_1_national-harbor-casino-site-casino-measure|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=17 November 2012|author2=T.W. Farnam}}</ref> and local officials.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chen|first=David W.|title=Manhattan Borough President Is Still Aiming High|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/09/nyregion/stringer-girds-for-a-run-for-mayor.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=8 January 2012}}</ref> Internationally, he has advised presidential and prime ministerial candidates in Africa, Asia, Central America and Europe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Anderson|first=Heather|title=Obama<U+2019>s senior adviser to discuss political advertising at Dole Institute event|url=http://archive.news.ku.edu/2011/april/8/margolis.shtml|newspaper=KU News|date=8 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dobbins|first=Elizabeth|title=OTC with Jim Margolis, OC <U+2019>78, and Senior Advisor to President Obama|url=http://oberlinreview.org/article/otc-jim-margolis-oc-78-and-senior-advisor-presiden/|newspaper=Oberlin Review|date=15 February 2013}}</ref>

In U.S. presidential politics, Margolis worked as deputy director of communications for Walter Mondale in 1986.<ref>{{cite news|last=Teinowitz|first=Ira|title=The Player: Kerry camp taps Margolis to devise media strategy|url=http://adage.com/article/news/player-kerry-camp-taps-margolis-devise-media-strategy/49086/|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=12 May 2013}}</ref> In 1992, the firm was the lead agency for President Clinton<U+2019>s presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Anderson|first=Heather|title=Obama<U+2019>s senior adviser to discuss political advertising at Dole Institute event|url=http://archive.news.ku.edu/2011/april/8/margolis.shtml|newspaper=KU News|date=8 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Methods of Margolis|url=http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2012/05/07/us/politics/201205007-margolis.html?_r=1&#/#link_0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=7 May 2012}}</ref> Margolis served as a senior strategist and lead media consultant for Senator John Kerry<U+2019>s 2004 presidential primary campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Teinowitz|first=Ira|title=The Player: Kerry camp taps Margolis to devise media strategy|url=http://adage.com/article/news/player-kerry-camp-taps-margolis-devise-media-strategy/49086/|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=12 May 2003}}</ref> During the 2004 Democratic primaries, <U+201C>Margolis<U+2019> commercials featuring Senator John Kerry<U+2019>s crewmates from Vietnam recalling his heroism were credited with helping him win the nomination."<ref>{{cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|title=Aggressive Ads for Obama, at the Ready|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/09/us/politics/obamas-media-team-has-aggressive-ads-at-the-ready.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 May 2012}}</ref> The primary ads produced by Margolis were considered <U+201C>to be the best on TV."<ref>{{cite news|last=Lizza|first=Ryan|title=A Victory for Shrum? [Bob Shrum consolidates his control of all Kerry advertising]|url=http://www.freerepublic.com/focus/f-news/1110266/posts|newspaper=New Republic Online|date=4 April 2004}}</ref> He left the Kerry race after the nomination was effectively won (April 2004), after a dispute with Robert Shrum, another media consultant.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lizza|first=Ryan|title=Rope-a-Dope|url=http://www.newrepublic.com/article/rope-dope|publisher=New Republic|accessdate=3 May 2004}}</ref> In the 2008 and 2012 campaigns, Margolis was a senior advisor to Barack Obama where he <U+201C>helped craft, hone and sell President Obama<U+2019>s message"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Methods of Margolis|url=http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2012/05/07/us/politics/201205007-margolis.html?_r=1&|newspaper=The New York Times|date=7 May 2012}}</ref> and <U+201C>was an indispensable part of Mr. Obama<U+2019>s media team."<ref>{{cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|title=Aggressive Ads for Obama, at the Ready|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/09/us/politics/obamas-media-team-has-aggressive-ads-at-the-ready.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 May 2012}}</ref> He <U+201C>relentlessly bombarded swing-state airwaves for months,<U+201D><ref>{{cite news|last=Scherer|first=Michael|title=2012 Person of the Year: Barack Obama, the President  Read more: 2012 Person of the Year: Barack Obama, the President {{!}} TIME.com http://poy.time.com/2012/12/19/person-of-the-year-barack-obama/#ixzz2l7C9iXq3|url=http://poy.time.com/2012/12/19/person-of-the-year-barack-obama/#ixzz2S4aToyTu|newspaper=Time Magazine|date=19 December 2012}}</ref> <U+201C>outfoxing Mitt Romney and his allies to air far more television spots despite being outspent,<U+201D> and was named one of <U+201C>The Obama Campaign<U+2019>s Real Heroes<U+201D> by Rolling Stone Magazine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dickinson|first=Tim|title=The Obama Campaign's Real Heroes|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/the-obama-campaigns-real-heroes-20121126|newspaper=Rolling Stone|date=7 December 2012}}</ref>

According to the New York Times, <U+201C>If you live in a state where a presidential contest has been close at some point in the last 20 years, you have probably seen one of Mr. Margolis<U+2019>s ads."<ref>{{cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|title=Aggressive Ads for Obama, at the Ready|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/09/us/politics/obamas-media-team-has-aggressive-ads-at-the-ready.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=9 May 2012}}</ref>

== Non-Profit and Corporate Work ==
At GMMB, Margolis has advised non-profit and foundation clients including The Center for the Next Generation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Lizza|first=Ryan|title=THE POLITICAL SCENE: THE PRESIDENT AND THE PIPELINE|url=http://willsull.net/la370/resources/Equity/RyanLizza.pdf|date=16 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Flock|first=Elizabeth|title=Former Bush and Obama Advisors Team Up To Produce Provocative New Ads About Kids|url=http://www.usnews.com/news/blogs/washington-whispers/2012/11/14/former-bush-and-obama-advisors-team-up-to-produce-provocative-new-ads-about-kids|newspaper=U.S. News & World Report|date=14 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Russell|first=Mallory|title=Obama, Bush Advisers Craft Shocking Children's Advocacy Ad|url=http://adage.com/article/news/obama-bush-advisers-craft-shocking-children-s-advocacy-ad/238305/|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=14 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Margolis|first=Jim|title=Don't forget America's kids|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1112/83869.html|newspaper=Politico|date=15 November 2012|author2=Mark McKinnon}}</ref> The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Goetzl|first=David|title=Media Strategist Margolis Muses On Obama Campaign|url=http://www.mediapost.com/publications/article/108182/media-strategist-margolis-muses-on-obama-campaign.html#axzz2cd4XXXnP|newspaper=MediaDailyNews|date=17 June 2009}}</ref> The Kaiser Family Foundation, The Sierra Club, The Corporation for National and Community Service, AARP,<ref>{{cite news|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING -- ADDENDA; Fleishman-Hillard Buys Greer, Margolis|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/26/business/the-media-business-advertising-addenda-fleishman-hillard-buys-greer-margolis.html?n=Top%252fReference%252fTimes%20Topics%252fSubjects%252fF%252fFinances&pagewanted=print|newspaper=The New York Times|date=26 December 2000}}</ref> the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Teinowitz|first=Ira|title=The Player: Kerry camp taps Margolis to devise media strategy|url=http://adage.com/abstract?article_id=49086|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=12 May 2003}}</ref> and the Walmart Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title=MANAGING A SUCCESSFUL CAMPAIGN FROM THE COURTHOUSE TO THE WHITE HOUSE|url=http://www.iop.harvard.edu/managing-successful-campaign-courthouse-white-house|publisher=Harvard University, Institute of Politics|accessdate=4 March 2009}}</ref>

Corporate clients have included AT&T, MGM Resorts International,<ref>{{cite news|last=Arsenault|first=Mark|title=MGM woos Springfield voters|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/04/09/mgm-pushing-hard-springfield-public-campaign/NW6R6GiZSU0sa8RHFTqaZI/story.html|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=10 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Trygstad|first=Kyle|title=Shop Talk: The Winning and Losing Consultants of the '12 Cycle|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/shop_talk_the_winning_and_losing_consultants_of_the_12_cycle-219079-1.html?zkPrintable=true|newspaper=Roll Call|date=13 November 212}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Aaron C.|title=Politically connected firms hit jackpot in Maryland casino fight|url=http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2012-11-17/local/35503824_1_national-harbor-casino-site-casino-measure|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=17 November 2012|author2=T.W. Farnam}}</ref> FINRA, Kaiser Permanente, Cisco Systems,<ref>{{cite news|last=Teinowitz|first=Ira|title=The Player: Kerry camp taps Margolis to devise media strategy|url=http://adage.com/article/news/player-kerry-camp-taps-margolis-devise-media-strategy/49086/|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=4 March 2009}}</ref> and VISA.<ref>{{cite web|title=MANAGING A SUCCESSFUL CAMPAIGN FROM THE COURTHOUSE TO THE WHITE HOUSE|url=http://www.iop.harvard.edu/managing-successful-campaign-courthouse-white-house|publisher=Harvard University, Institute of Politics|accessdate=4 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Brister|first=Kathy|title=Visa's Image Overhaul|url=http://www.americanbanker.com/magazine/120_1/ad-beat-visas-image-overhaul-1005358-1.html|newspaper=American Banker|date=1 January 2010}}</ref> Labor organizations including AFSCME, the UAW and CWA have worked with Margolis on organizing, communications and crisis management issues.<ref>{{cite web|title=MANAGING A SUCCESSFUL CAMPAIGN FROM THE COURTHOUSE TO THE WHITE HOUSE|url=http://www.iop.harvard.edu/managing-successful-campaign-courthouse-white-house|publisher=Harvard University, Institute of Politics|accessdate=4 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rozansky|first=Michael L.|title=Union Wages A War Of Ads Rather Than Strike, The Cwa Is Attacking Bell Atlantic's Image.|url=http://articles.philly.com/1995-12-24/business/25668371_1_cwa-bell-atlantic-union-workers|newspaper=The Inquirer|date=24 December 1995}}</ref>

